{"text": "nostalgia hit like truck", "appid": "2990", "steamid": "profiles/76561198429581441", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1599998400.0}
{"text": "Didn't know what to expect in terms of audio. It was a pleasant surprise to hear the intro music and the music for each locale. Each of tracks to the locations represented each location's \"feel\" and theme very well. The music is very well made that it somehow stuck itself in head like bumping 90's track. Minor gripe: A certain enemy type that has a high pitched battle intro sound, that's all. As it is a game with a party system, you can expect variation in each character's strength and weakness. As for me I can't seem to work out the importance/strength of this one character that you will encounter in one of the first few locales. So I will usually alternate between every other character to play to their strengths when encountering different enemies except for this one character. Banter/Interactions between characters is what makes them memorable. However I felt that it toned down a tad bit as the game progresses. Battles have a turn-based combat system reminiscent of other RPG-Maker games (which isn't a bad thing necessarily) Where you have the general \"attack\", \"special/magic\", \"guard\" moves etc and also to which you can try to escape from combat when things turn sour. After each combat it will yield you with experience points and items that the enemy drops. These items then can be sold to acquire potions, rings etc. A minor gripe: The item system, you will find yourself selling a lot of those item drops from battles because it doesn't have any use to them. If you play too much RPG games you might find yourself feeling that more could be done with those items, such as a crafting system where you can make special potions, enchant a ring or something along those lines. But if you can overlook that aspect then there won't be an issue at all. Since the game does not have any difficulty settings, I was surprised to see certain locations that has really challenging enemies if you happen to enter those locations a little to early. So do expect a small portion of the game to level up your characters before you progress into a new area or you would find your party decimated over and over. Getting into this game to beta test it, I was expecting (not hoping) to encounter certain bugs or maybe even a typo here and there in the dialogue. However much to my surprise, there wasn't any bugs encountered which was breath of fresh air, wish the same thing can be said about my house. As with other RPG-Maker games you get what you see in terms of the graphics of the game. The art style is up at the standard of other good RPG-Maker & Visual Novels you can think of. Don't let the initial clich√© start of the story stop you from playing as it gains momentum as the minutes tick by. The initial clich√© start will be a distant memory as story pans out. A good note to take is that I expected the game to on the range of 6-8 hours but that doesn't seem to be the case as it is rather longer than I had expected but that could also vary from each player's play style. For a person who is easily put off from an RPG-Maker game like how some people are put off with pixel graphics games, I would say to give this game a shot if you're open to trying and giving a game of this nature a chance and who knows you might be finding yourself having some fun relaxing time in this game. The minor gripes stated above is based on personal preference that can be overlooked and vary from person to person. But with a game that is fundamentally & mechanically well made as this, its hard to not recommend it.", "appid": "378830", "steamid": "profiles/76561198089256397", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1438344000.0}
