{"text": "is a short   that requires little in terms of button inputs. You walk/run around semi-open levels and occasionally press a button to dig something up or jump to reach elevated areas. There's an additional mechanic, where you can \"pick up\" butterflies, by simply walking over them, that boost the height of your next jump. Sadly, the sections that should require these butterflies to progress allow you to easily just skip them, since you can reach many places you shouldn't, even without the boost. A bit more thorough play-testing would've surely allowed the developer to prevent this from happening, as skipping those sections can feel like the natural thing to do but will keep some of the dialogue from you and also reduce the play time. Additionally you can pick up small orbs of light that are scattered throughout the world and will serve a particular purpose at a late point in the game. We explore a dream of the narrator, Joseph, as he describes it to his wife. In the dream we follow a fox looking for her missing cubs, traversing differently themed landscapes, uncovering different mementos of Joseph's past along the way. By uncovering these keepsakes, we uncover more about Joseph's childhood through his narration with one clear thread connecting the memories. At the same time, by following the fox mother on her tragic journey, we get closer to uncovering the truth about Joseph's current situation. The slightly surreal art-style, with objects from the real world being slightly desaturated when compared to the rest, the mixing of the fox' story and Joseph's, as well as the sudden transitions between the levels help to create a somewhat dreamlike atmosphere, but the game could've been a lot less subtle about it. As it is, it seems a bit bland at times. The narration, which is done by the game's solo developer and his wife, is really touching, on the other hand, and it feels like the story of Joseph may take a lot of inspiration from that of developer David Wehle. Sadly, some of the areas seem a little too spaced out, considering the movement speed and the low-key   mentality the game induces with it's pickups and light orbs. The game offers good graphics, some well-done animations and a beautiful simplistic art-style that manages to create a lot of atmosphere. It doesn't manage to be exceptional in any of those aspects, though. The graphics are good for the most part but some textures seem either washed out or lacking any detail. Additionally assets like trees are often copy+pasted into the world excessively, and some objects aren't properly connected to the floor when placed on slopes, making the under-/inside of them visible in places. I've also encountered a really weird looking house, with a roof texture that was probably intended for use for watermelons. Something like the animalistic animations, that are done well enough in here, can't even hope to compete to something like   for example and while walking and running do look great, the jumping and especially landing animations are less than perfect. The art-style is quite beautiful but fails to really stick out to me, measured against something like  ,  ,   or  . There are a couple of nice stylistic choices involved in the game and two scenes near the end of the game do look pretty stunning. It is a very pleasant experience overall, nonetheless, but it has room for improvement. The gentle and melancholic   tracks that accompany the game perfectly manage to sound peaceful and tranquil on a first play-through but very subtly carry sad undertones that really kick in as soon as you know what the story is partly about.   created something truly beautiful and touching. This game is mainly for fans of   as well as lovers of a touching story. The game runs at a constant ~60 frames per second on the highest graphical settings with some drops to ~50 or even ~40 frames in two certain areas of the game. On lower settings the game doesn't suffer from any frame drops and runs really smoothly. Even lower-end computers shouldn't have too hard of a time with the game. Tested with the following setup:  is a bit of mixed bag, with many things to like but almost as many things to hold it back. For the emotional, good voice acting, the amazing soundtrack, the touching story and the not quite unique but still pretty art-style alone, I'd still recommend it to every friend of  .", "appid": "555150", "steamid": "profiles/76561198008869914", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "93", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1585915200.0}
