{"text": "\"Forever Alpha\" Scroll up and you'll see that the release date of this Alpha was December 16, 2013. So just over 2 years. You know what games run on a 2 year dev cycle? Call of Duty, for example. Made with hundreds of developers and the finanical support of a multi-billion publishing corporation. This game has one of THE most open developments of all time. You can read dev blogs on their website  . Wanna know what else takes a lot of time? Developing a game engine. The DayZ developers are redesigning the entire engine. I don't mean they're simply replacing the engine like The Dead Linger or Rust. No, they are adding their own custom modules. Physics is a third party software, network architecture is scratch coded, and they are in the process of replacing the graphics and audio renderers. This takes longer than ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô• game development and yet they're not only doing this but ALSO developing a game simultaneously and people have the audacity to say they're 'taking too long'? Hah, As for the state of the game now, it's playable, they have stable and experimental branches. It's fun with friends. If you can enjoy a game with bugs (You know, like any of the STALKER series or Bethesda games) then I'm sure you could have fun with this. Otherwise wait until Beta or final release.", "appid": "221100", "steamid": "profiles/76561198001836794", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1424779200.0}
