{"text": "This really game really was a hidden gem, not only is the main character a Horse but the storyline is written beautifully. The shooting mechanics are perfect and the hit markers indicate whether you have hit a person or not. The aim assist is extremely helpful and helps you when you are doing extremely well in multiplayer games when playing against your friends or random opponents. The ranking system is fenominal and very rewarding, when your character has reached a maximum rank you can throw all of your hard earned work away and do it all again... 15 times!! it's brilliant! The multiplayer also offers killstreaks a system rewarded to players for there good plays In fact, the killstreaks themselves are evidence that the game's balance is truly there. Killstreaks have been expanded from the original Goat Simulator, now allowing players to unlock rewards such as stealth bombers, AC-130 strikes, EMP blasts, and even a devastating 25 killstreak nuke that ends the game with a big bang, automatically handing your team the win if you can pull it off. The gameplay is smoother than ever you'll instantly get a sense of just how far the improved engine has come from the previous games.Goat Simulator is definitely more chaotic this time around ‚Äì partially due to the new visual effects and upped production values ‚Äì and with the improved enemy AI and tough scenario design you'll be fighting for every checkpoint. One of the larger visual changes to the game's heads-up display this time around is the blood splatter system, you'd get damaged, the screen would start to shade red, and you'd be required to seek cover before your vision returned to normal.  For the vast majority of the experience, Goat Simulator is best enjoyed with friends either locally or via online. The core campaign may have taken a bit of a hit, but in its place is an incredibly well done debut mode called Spec Ops. For those that don't know, Spec Ops mode is an arcade-inspired challenge mode that can be played single player for the most part (minus a few co-op specific challenges), but is obviously designed around two-person team play. The mode is broken up into five tiers, each with missions that have a possible three stars to gain based on difficulty level in each of the 23 missions. You'll see a lot of repeating areas, some pulled directly from the single-player campaign, but the actual objectives (and most of the time, the exact layout of the level) is all new. You won't find leaderboards for this mode, unfortunately. When you look at the total package, Goat Simulator is hands-down one of the best first-person shooters out there, and a truly amazing offering across any system.For the strictly single player crowd, however, Goat Simulator is surprisingly short, and doesn't live up to the standard set by previous Goat Simulator games. My final Verdict for this game is - 10/10 - IGN - Outstanding", "appid": "265930", "steamid": "profiles/76561198102546196", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": "5", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1437998400.0}
