{"text": "Forget about all these slow sequences from the other games, hell is unleashed at the very first minute after clicking start, and you will be firing big guns and slashing cyber katanas as fast as you can say Bubblegum crisis. Combat is fast, firing is fast, everything is fast but sometimes it is just total hardcore and then when the power metal and epic orchestra are saturating your senses, the pace stops. Good thing, so you can rest your mind from all the fighting so it can taste good again soon enough. Usually you must walk around a bit and even puzzle your way down, while some epic choir paves the way like a blockbuster movie as you unveil pieces of some ancient mysteries. Sometimes walking is a bit too much but that's just me wanting more and more action. Next room, repeat. You don't get it? It's a total legal addictive opioid with chances of causing vertigo. Bright Memory was mainly created by Xiancheng and his private studios after crowdfunding it, good sales made the project go further to a total reboot called Bright Memory: Infinite. It is important to spread the news of the awesomeness I've found on this ''demo'' directly to you so you can rip from future benefits and help us and it is also my intention to show to Xiancheng how I think this is looking super awesome and how I believe he can keep on that track. But I fear it may deviate too much. I was tired of triple A games asking for my credit card just for new poop to download and I needed some time alone with lesser games. I got disappointed very often even this way, because every indie game I tried was copying someone else ideas or they were just pathetic.  Now I find this one Bright Memory on the making, and my fellow sinner, you better be paying attention because I'm impressed and this is very unusual.  Plot has substance so far but I fear it will lose some of it for the sake of \"style\". Sometimes secret passages gives you hints of what's going on, I think its ancient aliens and/or evil dead civilizations and such and that's cool. Though I haven't seen many games were the baddies are really a bunch of despicable pieces of human waste, I just hate the main villain as I keep chasing him, so it means the plot works enough. It is on the bootleg side, but that's tradition for these types. I guess Doom did that right recently. But what pumps you on Doom is to know you're supposed to be the angry guy, so nothing else matters. So how do you get pumped with Bright Memory? The answer equals to that  Shelia is the bearer of that cyber armor powerhouse but her personality is boring (way too cute and polite) and doesn't fit all that. So I agree Shelia character design needs a rework. The problem now, she's leaving that ''Lara Croft'' looks and that is great. But as you can see here    she is going where I was fearing and that's worrisome. I'm not sure if that was what the developer was aiming at, but this is why companies avoid contacting fans too much let's say.  Shelia is going to the juvenile and overplayed world of collegial anime heroes and Sailor Moon or Sucker Punch stuff, like every other similar product from the past 30 years combined. Instead of giving her more personality maybe around the mature fidelity the demo has, she will just be looking like another overused teen stereotype with pig tails - when Bright Memory is actually a very original piece, and now this?  As long the game keeps going frenzy since I'm in for the hardcore and vicious battles. I like how graphics don't need big companies to look nice. But Unreal Engine 4 means sheat if you don't have creativity and knowledge, how to program it and how to properly connect every resource on the right way. If you don't know how to work with it you should mess with it first and study it, not just trial and error like most indie does. Fortunately for you, FYQD did all that and with extra material I call ''talent''. It is a rare magical element only possible to acquire at birth. Legend says those who possess talent are constantly bullied before they are accepted on this dumbo world. No need for false modesty here, the guy developed this on his \"spare time\". That's impressive. As you progress, experience points drops can be collected and it is possible and even optional to upgrade them (with little to no context) but the idea is to become a cyber goddess with the ultimate abilities. In the old days games like these were usually a total failure like Daikatana was. I feel a lot of arcadey hack and slash here but don't be fooled, it is a hybrid FPS trying to look different and I totally recommend you to go experience it. Don't expect the rifle to be the main point here, it is how you combo these skills that you're supposed to use. Some people are annoyed because the game's spoken language is Chinese. If you're one of them you should move to Mars. In a couple decades, maybe not even Mars will hold you and we will have to slur you somewhere else. Not every company or developer is North American or European, that's obvious. And not everyone got the money to fill the list with multiple voice actors like Ubisoft does. It is actually pretty fashion to play it and hear some different language and different everything like I did with Metro Last Light (although they had Eng voice there). I don't even believe I have to explain that to possible dummies. You got the subtitles anyway, so I don't get your problem.  If you got that problem ain't my problem, so deal with it. The game needs more of what you see on the first 10 minutes and I recommend less explorations. I agree you can have both as demonstrated by Doom 2016 (and by your own game) but that can be the core of the level you're in, thus optional - not necessarily the spaces in-between fights and paths. Don't bother with complaints about how the enemies keeps coming towards you, the enemies are very aggressive and this is exactly what a real FPS needs. On my opinion you're on the right track, keep the action as vicious as possible, keep going hardcore, add Sheila some personality and less schizophrenia (because she talks to herself too much) and you will be on the list for another legendary FPS soon enough. None so far. When it is time I make sure to report it with a new review once the full game is released or another part of it. I would love to see vivid looking cards like the game is and emoticons with enough shining varieties.", "appid": "955050", "steamid": "profiles/76561198061795684", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "22", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1569326400.0}
