{"text": "I remember the days, when combat racing games were all the hype. Those are early Blizzard days, when they've released the game I've mentioned above. They've truly opened a Pandora's box with that one. Formula of making a game like that hasn't changed since those days, too: you take your isometric camera, place it over a plainly shaped track, scatter some bonuses around, add very little to no car variation, and -- voila! -- your game is ready to be published. I realize, that the game I'm reviewing right now is 6 years old, but then again, so is  , another combat racing game, another Rock'n'Roll Racing rip-off. And while this game aged like milk, BlazeRush is still extremely fun to play, if you're into the genre. All in all, combat racing games are dead nowadays, cause no greedy published has yet found a way to add microtransactions or lootboxes to it (which does sound fairly easy, to think of it). As for the game, well, like I said: the formula hasn't changed since 1993. You grind cash on your races, you upgrade your car, you progress, open new tracks, buy new cars, upgrade further, rinse & repeat. Graphics are outdated, UI is plainly terrible, controls are too arcade (even for an arcade game), characters are something you'll forget as quickly as 10 seconds after turning off the game. Definitely not, there's a plenty of significantly better outdated combat racing games.", "appid": "284930", "steamid": "profiles/76561198005271335", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1589630400.0}
