{"text": "What starts off as an interesting stealth game with a neat concept unfortunately fails in its execution. The most egregious factor are the clunky and imprecise controls. The clickable area for the different actions seems to be offset from the actual visual button, which gets especially annoying during the segments that do not play out turn-based. The other big part of the messy controls is the jumping. There is a tooltip in the game that specifically states \"The jump arc indicator lies.\" and obviously you aren't going to jump as planned, if there's enemies in the way. Unfortunately, there are so many other situations where unplanned jumps aren't obvious at all. * You can jump through certain platforms, but only at a very specific angle, otherwise you'll just do a small hop to the side and get shot. * You can jump down while hanging from the ceiling, unless you again only do a small hop to the side. * The indicator shows you landing well on top of a platform and instead you land hanging off of its side. These are just a few examples that seem to me like an attempt to hide the buggy controls by praising them as a feature. Generally, the level design is good, although a bit repetitive. The last level unfortuantely does away with all the well placed checkpoints that were present throughout the game. I understand why this decision was made, but that doesn't make it any less an exercise in frustration when most of your deaths can be ascribed to the controls. All of these issues lead me to leave Ronin unfinished and instead recommend Gunpoint, which - although a bit different - is fun throughout.", "appid": "274230", "steamid": "profiles/76561197971088333", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "9", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1498651200.0}
