{"text": "There is no conditional recommendation feature on Steam, because of this I cannot recommend, however the program can be useful to would be flight simmers. The idea behind Dovetail Games Flight School is to give newcomers to the genre a taste of what flight sims are all about at a reasonable price. For me it misses the mark, though the price is reasonable. The program offers the ability to gain two pilots licences by completing various tasks that form part of the basic mechanics of general aviation flying. It doesn‚Äôt give much by way of an understanding though, it is good at telling you what to do, but not as good at telling you why. The program also offers a number of missions of varying difficulty. These are fun, but are at the same time quite frustrating. Finally the program also offers the ability to freely fly anywhere on the planet using the two (soon to be three) supplied aircraft. I have used the program for just over 9 hours at the time of writing and my overall experience can only be described as one of frustration. I have over a thousand hours under my belt with FSX:SE and FSX before it, I found the amount of information made available to the pilot prior to any task or mission lacking. Simple things, like what the heading is of the runway you are being sent to for a mission, some of the strips are very tight. If you aren‚Äôt able to set up a good approach it just makes things more difficult and frustrating.  In the lessons, you don‚Äôt get to find out exactly what you are going to do until you are trying to trim the aircraft, monitor the speed/throttle and check your heading while the instructor is also filling you in on the facts as to why you are in the air in the first place. This usually results in a failure of that particular mission/task, lots of swearing at the monitor and another attempt. At least you have a better understanding of what the objective is second or third time round. Now I haven‚Äôt been to flight school IRL, I do think though that I would receive a full briefing of what todays lesson was going to be before I got anywhere near the aircraft. If you can ride the waves of frustration and persevere with the lessons/missions, there is a sense of achievement upon completion. If you do this, there is a good chance that you will enjoy a step up to FSX, P3D, X-Plane or DTG‚Äôs upcoming Flight Simulator, so maybe the program is really just one big test. Despite community hub complaints, I find the graphics far better than many of the available flight sims that have global coverage out of the box. Just make sure your rig comfortably meets the spec requirements and you will have access to a program that performs and looks as good as a ¬£100+ spend on other sims for the sweet price of ¬£11, though there is room for some improvement (clouds, sky, mid-day ambient lighting). To summarise. It‚Äôs a cheap way to find out if you are willing to shell out substantially more on a good flight simulator. If you can put up with the programs foibles it is a good indication that this genre is for you. <TL;DR> If you are just testing the water for flight simming this will put you off more than encourage you to progress. If you think it is something you really want to get into, a little perseverance will help in making your mind up. </TL;DR>", "appid": "441920", "steamid": "profiles/76561198030867254", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "82", "votes_funny": "5", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1464436800.0}
