{"text": "Tuttifrutti Interactive devs hire interns to hunt for people who play hidden object puzzle games and bribe them with a free key so they can write an \"honest\" - which is a totally dishonest positive review for Darkata. One of their interns with only 2 games in his library and level 1 profile found me and tried convincing me to play Darkarta, a game that came out in 2017 and that nobody cares about. When I told him I don't have this game in my library, he felt bad for me and out of complete pureness of his angelic heart and beautiful soul offered me a free key. On one condition though - if I promised to write an honest review. Nice chat with the intern: The devs banned my screenshot with the nice person for a reason - because they can't ban reviews. If they could, they would. A lot of positive reviews are coming from low level (lvl 1 - lvl 2) profiles that have 1-2 games in their library and no other reviews but \"Darkarta\". When I wrote this review on November 15th, 2020, today (November 17th, 2020) in two days alone, Darkarta gained 8 more fake positive reviews. Darkarta - a mediocre HOG game that came out in 2017 that nobody cares about. So here is my honest review: This game is just as generic as most hidden object games, the cheesy story and hollow characters, puzzles that don't make sense, bad voice acting, badly rendered scenes, strong & independent businesswoman. Nothing new here. If you're making a game to just grub a few bucks, what are you gaining from fake positive reviews? Does it feel good reading them knowing that you bribe people with free copies of your games? Why not just own up to it and accept your piece of art as it is? Why trick potential buyers with fake positive reviews?", "appid": "601530", "steamid": "profiles/76561198083490861", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "8", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1605441600.0}
